I was surprised that I liked the movies so much. The fourth book was not my favorite by far, but the movies, especially the second part, were AWESOME!

Ever since I read the epic disaster that was "Breaking Dawn," I have been eagerly anticipating these movies. It was one of the vilest, silliest, grossest books I've ever read in my life, and I assumed that the movie would at least be funny. I mean, there's a scene where Edward chews open Bella's uterus!

Well, "The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn - Parts 1 and 2" managed to disappoint me. While there are some jaw-droppingly stupid moments, most of this two-part story is blindingly dull -- there's more padding than actual story here, riddled with painfully awkward acting, monotonous sex scenes, and lots of important topics (like abortion) that the writers aren't NEARLY smart enough to address. Also: the most anticlimactic ending EVER.

Bella (Kristen Stewart) and Edward (Robert Pattinson) are finally getting married... which we see every boring awkward moment of. After flying off to a private island (not kidding), they finally have sex. But then, Bella unexpectedly gets pregnant (sex leads to pregnancy? WHAT A TWIST!). Except Rosalie, the Cullens all want her to abort the monster baby, but Bella refuses to do so even though it's killing her (and no, nobody suggests a Caesarian. Why? Because "Twilight").

But the discovery that a monster baby is killing Bella somehow causes the werewolves to attack, because for some reason they care about all this. Oh, and aforementioned uterus-chewing scene.

But don't worry: Bella later wakes up a vampire, and she's the speshulest and sparkliest of all. However, her creepy kid with Edward attracts the attention of the Volturi, who have forbidden the making of any vampire children -- and now they're coming to Forks to wipe them out. So the Cullens call in all their friends (none of whom have EVER been introduced before) to help them make a final stand. Or not.

The worst thing about these dreadful movies is that they broke the ludicrous "Breaking Dawn" story into two separate movies. This works when you have an epic story ("The Hobbit") or a plot-heavy one ("Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows"). But for a tween-porn romance about how special Bella is for having a functioning uterus, it's the kiss of death.

So to fill out all the space NOT occupied by plot or characterization, the movie is crammed with padding. Lots of padding. Endless padding. Even the SEX feels like it has been padded -- I spent most of the PG-13 sex scenes wondering if Bella would ever change expression during sex (and no, she didn't). And even when the Volturi learn of the Creepy Demonspawn's existence, the padding doesn't go away. Instead we're treated to endless scenes of new vampires hanging around the Cullen mansion, showing off their sooper-kewl powers to the audience.

I will give director Bill Condon some credit -- he does try to lessen the grotesquely hellish birth scene, and the subsequent pedophilic squick of Jacob "imprinting" on a newborn baby. Additionally, he created a truly riveting, graphically violent climax for the second movie that is frankly pretty awesome... until you discover it was all a dream. Yes, we're left with no resolution whatsoever. Everyone just goes home.

The acting is pretty much what you would expect by now. Kristen Stewart is awkward, mumbly, graceless and incapable of moving her face like a human being, and Robert Pattinson looks bored and detached. His character's true repulsiveness is revealed in full here -- not only is Edward a controlling misogynistic stalker, but he tries to emotionally blackmail his wife into getting an abortion. Mr. Dreamy!

Taylor Lautner's Jacob also loses what shreds of likability he had, when suddenly he discovers he's the Troo Luv of a newborn baby. Ew. There are actually a lot of good smaller performances -- mostly from the random "new" vampires who pop up to help the Cullens -- but they're pretty much wasted. But Michael Sheen is hilarious -- his campy, cackling, bug-eyed performance is absolutely delightful.

"The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn Part 1 & 2" takes a plotless lump of drivel, and stretches it out over two full-length movies -- but let's face it, it would have been a disaster even as one. Avoid these movies like you owe them money.

Walmart has this exact same set for $22.96 plus shipping, which comes to $24 and some change all together. The Blu ray set is only a couple of dollars more. Do not buy this set from Amazon for $49.99 with free 2 day shipping.

This is available to buy from other sellers, so it you want to order it through Amazon that's probably the best thing to do because then you'll be getting it even cheaper. I saw one for $20.36 with shipping.

Oh and BTW, if you get this edition, Breaking Dawn Part 2 will not include any special features, which in this case would be the 7 part documentary. It will not be included in this set. You will be getting Breaking Dawn Part 1 - The Extended Edition and Breaking Dawn Part 2 the movie. That's it.

The Twilight Saga inclusive is a masterpiece story written by Stephenie Meyers. The movies are amazingly true to each of the books.  What's noteworthy is decision to go with 4 different directors to tell the story installments, yet never losing grip of the saga. My review for each of the Twilight movies are EXCELLENT.  By the way, the books were recommended to me by a fellow teacher, which surprised me because we're both not "spring chickens" (LOL).  But I saw it as excellent in content and technique as any American movie classic. If you love screen soundtracks and scores, you'll also love the use of music techniques for each of the movies.

I was very excited to get the extended version of both movies in one package.  The product title is "The Twilight Saga: Breaking Dawn, Parts 1 & 2 (Extended Edition)"  So naturally I was expecting to get the extended edition of both Part 1 and Part 2.

Very disappointed.  The extended edition only applied to Part 1.  So the title was misleading.  If you look closely at the package cover it only mentions the extended edition under part one.  I don't know about you, but I don't normally go searching the product images to figure out if they are trying to slip one past me.
